category.name: Vision & Strategy
category.description: Develops an ambitious but realistic business vision and translates it into a workable strategy

sub_competency.name: Vision & Strategy
sub_competency.description: Develops an ambitious but realistic business vision and translates it into a workable strategy
sub_competency.score_description:
(Name) is appreciative of new ideas and solutions, but is more inclined to build upon innovative/novel ideas of others than developing own original solutions, to create a compelling vision and strategy.
(Name) is likely able to paint a picture of the way forward when required by promoting clear and compelling vision and strategy, at the same time motivating and engaging others into action, however (Name) may not be inclined to do so proactively.
(Name) is likely able to work around concepts, connecting the dots to formulate a comprehensible and compelling vision and strategy, driving the way forward, though (Name) is more inclined to focus on the practical visions/strategies.
(Name) is likely able to lead others in the right direction towards fulfilling the vision and strategy, role modelling while motivating and engaging others into action when required to, but otherwise prefers to follow the lead.
sub_competency.development_tips:
Be clear within yourself about your vision for the way forward before you communicate it  to others. Engage with trusted colleagues to gather their thoughts and ideas, ask for constructive criticism. List your thoughts and reflections, and adjust your plan so you have a clear and compelling vision to present.

Step up and take responsibility for leading people towards a vision or stretching goal. How will you make sure you and the team stay on course?  

Take a strategy or part of a vision and consider ways to engage and motivate different individuals to take an active part in progressing this. How can you adapt your style or behaviour to meet different needs? Look at the ways others do this; what can you learn from them? What other techniques can you adopt? Experiment with a variety of methods to see which work best.

category.name: Bottom-line Focus
category.description: Focuses on bottom-line results, identifies potential risks and monitors the financial impact of own activities

sub_competency.name: Bottom-line Focus
sub_competency.description: Focuses on bottom-line results, identifies potential risks and monitors the financial impact of own activities
sub_competency.score_description:
With the end target in mind, (Name) has a tendency to strongly focus on achieving defined objectives while adhering to timelines, prioritising and approaching tasks and issues quickly and effectively.
With a tendency to pay attention to task importance, (Name) can be depended on to see tasks through to the end to fulfill objectives, adhering to defined plans, timelines and procedures.
(Name) is inclined to approach tasks in a systematic and well-organised manner, defining clear priorities, objectives and timelines according to urgency and importance of tasks, formulating concrete action steps and contingency plans whilst anticipating potential obstacles.
(Name) is inclined to consider the urgency and importance of tasks, while prioritising tasks with a broad and long-term perspective, taking into account a wide range of factors and potential risks, producing plans in advance with clearly defined objectives and timelines.
sub_competency.development_tips:
During project management, this competency is deemed very much important in achieving milestones. This area tends to drive results, while tracking deliverables and progress. 

However the ongoing question is often how to prioritise task when everything is topped as no. 1? In hindsight, your scores suggest you have preference in this area. As such, have a project management software come to your rescue. Motivate your team to have a platform to track and monitor project progress using a guided software to better encourage planning and prioritising. Just like any good behaviour, to further reinforce one, do implement reward systems etc to encourage usage as it will also aid in optimising results.

category.name: People Development
category.description: Develops people through delegation, empowerment and coaching; promotes career and self development

sub_competency.name: People Development
sub_competency.description: Develops people through delegation, empowerment and coaching; promotes career and self development
sub_competency.score_description:
(Name) may consider it less important that people are always treated fairly in the organisation, hence may not focus so much on fairness when delegating tasks and may overlook to consider individual needs for development.
(Name) likely prefers others taking charge, hence (Name) may shy away from managing others, delegating tasks and clarifying accountabilities, as well as tracking progress.
(Name) tends to place more emphasis on tasks than on people elements at work and may be less inclined to invest time into understanding individual needs or personal strengths and weaknesses, hence (Name) could face challenges in managing and developing others. 
As (Name) dislikes being the centre of attention and may be seen as uncertain, (Name) may find it uncomfortable managing and developing different groups of people as well as encouraging them to perform at their best. 
With a tendency to put more focus on getting the best outcome and to consider different factors, (Name) may get caught up with work details and miss out on opportunities to manage and develop people whilst keeping them accountable on their tasks.
sub_competency.development_tips:
Map out a strategy on how to better assign tasks to people with different levels of knowledge, skills and experiences. Do this by communicating with them to gain a strong understanding of their abilities, what it is they enjoy doing most, and where they need more exposure in the business. Discuss tasks with them regularly.

Understand the direction of the performance of individuals in your team. Keep track of their progress on tasks and set up a process to monitor their workload. Give feedback to team members and address the issue with those who are not on track with their work. Meet underperforming individuals and explore the reasons behind this without demotivating them; show encouragement and remind them of the business's expectations. Work with them to find a solution to the issues. 

Map out your goals for the team and assign challenging tasks to keep them engaged and to make them feel included in the team. Balance offering assistance with a sense of autonomy.

category.name: Organizational Awareness
category.description: Develops people through delegation, empowerment and coaching; promotes career and self development

sub_competency.name: Organizational Awareness
sub_competency.description: Develops people through delegation, empowerment and coaching; promotes career and self development
sub_competency.score_description:
Though (Name) may overlook the long-term aspects and effect of decisions and actions on other parts of the organisation, (Name) tends to be aware of key factors in the people, structure and cultural context of the organisation.
(Name) generally has some interest in understanding the people and cultural context of the organisation, their behaviour and motivations as well as the organisational politics, but could pay more attention on the effect of decisions and actions on the people parts of the organisation while navigating the influence dynamics of the organisation.
(Name) is likely to understand the people, structure and cultural context of the organisation, regularly engaging with the people at work, however (Name) may face some difficulties navigating the influence dynamics within unfamiliar environments in the organisation.
(Name) has a likelihood of understanding the people, structure and cultural context of the organisation from a big picture viewpoint, but (Name) tends to focus more on implementation of decisions/actions into practice.
sub_competency.development_tips:
Find out what is happening across all parts of the organisation, exploring other functions and how they work. Make time to understand the company's culture, business processes, values, mission and vision, as well as the interdependencies of these elements and how they make up the organisation. From there, look at these relationships from a wider perspective to understand how the decisions and actions of one part impact other parts of the organisation.

Keep up-to-date with activities that are going on in your company, for example, new product launches, business updates, new technology and marketing initiatives. This will heighten your knowledge of the organisation. 

Engage in activities such as breakfast or lunch talks to discuss matters concerning the organisation and its business. Consider hosting one about your own function or department, to introduce other parts of the business to what you do.

category.name: Innovation
category.description: Produces fresh and imaginative ideas and solutions; breaks away from tradition; promotes change and novelty

sub_competency.name: Innovation
sub_competency.description: Produces fresh and imaginative ideas and solutions; breaks away from tradition; promotes change and novelty
sub_competency.score_description: (Name) is appreciative of new and novel ideas and solutions, helping others to visualise their new ideas, however, (Name) is more inclined to rely on the ideas of others, building upon them rather than generating own original ideas.\n(Name) is generally open to new and novel ideas/solutions or processes, however (Name) may still prefer the value of existing well-proven solutions, as (Name) may not prefer change for its own sake.\n(Name) tends to be able to attune to conceptual and abstract ideas and solutions, though (Name) is more inclined to focus on the implementation into practice, hence may only help others visualise ideas and possibilities that are tangible.
sub_competency.development_tips:
Have a clear understanding of your work and find new ways to improve the way you and the wider team go about your activities. Share ideas and explore initiatives thoroughly before critiquing them or shutting them down. Come up with a number of alternative ideas and then review them for quality.

Be open to new ideas from others and encourage brainstorming with colleagues. Facilitate cross-functional discussion and encourage people to connect in unusual ways to share changes and innovations they have introduced in their area. Examine whether these can be applied in your area of work.   

Read up on the latest insights in your work and related areas. Find a colleague that you feel comfortable with and encourage each other to try out new things, regardless of the scale of it. It can be as simple as creating a new template, or on a larger scale, creating a new process to increase efficiency for your whole department. Communicate the new idea to others in your area.

category.name: Effective Communication
category.description: Communicates in a clear, precise and structured way; speaks with authority and conviction; presents effectively

sub_competency.name: Effective Communication
sub_competency.description: Communicates in a clear, precise and structured way; speaks with authority and conviction; presents effectively
sub_competency.score_description:
(Name) is likely able to communicate clear messages while influencing others with some confidence and impact when necessary, but may not do so proactively.
Fairly mindful of people's reaction and motives, (Name) is likely able to communicate messages convincingly, adapting them to the target audience, however could be more attentive as (Name) may at times overlook some opinions of others.
(Name) generally tends to be able to make sense of various topics and opinions of people, simplifying them into a comprehensive manner to communicate clear and concise messages.
When in familiar environments (Name) tends to be at ease putting forth clear and concise messages with confidence and impact, however (Name) may be more self-controlled when presenting messages in unfamiliar environments.
(Name) sees open communication as important factor but may not necessary believe that people always have to be adequately informed about all matters, hence (Name) may usually communicate clearly and concisely but may hold back information from certain people.
sub_competency.development_tips:
Pick a well-known role model giving a speech, presentation or TED talk. What body language do they use? How do they convey the message they want to get across? What visual aids do they use?

Make a list of their actions, body language, language choices, and other reasons people find them good communicators. Experiment with some of the techniques and behaviours they use next time you give a presentation and get feedback from your audience.

Manage your emotions while communicating with others - keep stress in check during tough situations, such as a job interview or a business presentation and articulate your thoughts in a calm but effective manner.

Consider the audience you are communicating to and what your key messages are. Tailor your message using language, tone and a medium to suit the audience. Try to anticipate their reactions and objections in advance. Gather feedback from trusted colleagues on what worked well and what you could improve on.

competencies.name: Vision & Strategy

suggested_questions.name: Talk about a time when you created a direction for your team/organisation to follow when matters were disorganised/ambiguous.
sub_questions: What were the factors that you considered when creating the direction?
How did you communicate your direction to relevant parties?
What were the challenges that you encountered?
How did you overcome them?

suggested_questions.name: Share about an experience where you realigned your team/organisation to focus towards to a certain goal/objective.
sub_questions: What was the turning point/contributing factors for the realignment?
How did you develop the new objective/strategy?
What did you do to obtain other's commitment towards the new objective/strategy?
What were the outcome that you were able to bring through the realignment?

positive_indicators: Excels in creating a clear and compelling vision.
Takes responsibility for leading others to action on the vision.
Effective at engaging and inspiring others to buy-in into the vision.
Challenges status when needed to achieve vision.
negative_indicators: Vision and strategy may lack clarity and impact.
Prefers to focus on own goals and for others to lead people in the right direction.
May lose momentum and struggle to motivate others to action the vision and strategy.
competencies.score_description:
(Name) is appreciative of new ideas and solutions, but is more inclined to build upon innovative/novel ideas of others than developing own original solutions, to create a compelling vision and strategy.
(Name) is likely able to paint a picture of the way forward when required by promoting clear and compelling vision and strategy, at the same time motivating and engaging others into action, however (Name) may not be inclined to do so proactively.
(Name) is likely able to work around concepts, connecting the dots to formulate a comprehensible and compelling vision and strategy, driving the way forward, though (Name) is more inclined to focus on the practical visions/strategies.
(Name) is likely able to lead others in the right direction towards fulfilling the vision and strategy, role modelling while motivating and engaging others into action when required to, but otherwise prefers to follow the lead.

competencies.name: Bottom-line Focus

suggested_questions.name: Describe an experience where you were required to manage multiple important priorities at one time.
sub_questions: What were the challenges that you faced?
How did you manage the situation?
How effective was your efforts and what could you have done better?

suggested_questions.name: Share a time when you were assigned to manage a project/work initiative.
sub_questions: What was the project objectives and goals?
What action steps did you take from end to end?
What challenges did you face and how did you tackle them?
How did the project conclude in the end?

suggested_questions.name: Share a situation when you needed to accomodate a new task/assignment in the midst of juggling a few deadlines.
sub_questions: How did you go about assuming the new task/assignment?
How did you decide which tasks was more important for you to focus on?
How did you manage timeline and resources to accommodate the additional workload?
What was the outcome in the end, share about the pros and cons?

positive_indicators: Quickly understands the importance of tasks and prioritises effectively.
Approaches tasks in a highly organised and systematic way, and effectively tracks progress.
Produces exceptionally clear plans well in advance, with defined objectives and timelines.
negative_indicators: May struggle to identify the most urgent and important tasks and prioritise accordingly.
May overlook the importance of planning, tracking progress and working to timelines.
Prefers to work in a more flexible way, reacting to changing needs and requirements as they arise.
competencies.score_description:
With the end target in mind, (Name) has a tendency to strongly focus on achieving defined objectives while adhering to timelines, prioritising and approaching tasks and issues quickly and effectively.
With a tendency to pay attention to task importance, (Name) can be depended on to see tasks through to the end to fulfill objectives, adhering to defined plans, timelines and procedures.
(Name) is inclined to approach tasks in a systematic and well-organised manner, defining clear priorities, objectives and timelines according to urgency and importance of tasks, formulating concrete action steps and contingency plans whilst anticipating potential obstacles.
(Name) is inclined to consider the urgency and importance of tasks, while prioritising tasks with a broad and long-term perspective, taking into account a wide range of factors and potential risks, producing plans in advance with clearly defined objectives and timelines.

competencies.name: People Development

suggested_questions.name: Give me an example of a time when you contributed to the development of others.
sub_questions: What was your role in his/her development journey?
What approach did you use to support his/her development needs?
How was the person different from before as a result of your involvement?

positive_indicators: Highly effective in delegating tasks appropriate to individual levels of knowledge, skill and experience.
Excels in tracking and monitoring performance, holding individuals accountable.
Is exceptionally attentive to individual needs and is able to develop them to perform at their best.
negative_indicators: Overlooks delegating tasks and leaves it individuals to organise themselves.
Does not sufficiently monitor performance or hold individuals accountable.
Lacks awareness of individual development needs.
competencies.score_description:
(Name) may consider it less important that people are always treated fairly in the organisation, hence may not focus so much on fairness when delegating tasks and may overlook to consider individual needs for development.
(Name) likely prefers others taking charge, hence (Name) may shy away from managing others, delegating tasks and clarifying accountabilities, as well as tracking progress.
(Name) tends to place more emphasis on tasks than on people elements at work and may be less inclined to invest time into understanding individual needs or personal strengths and weaknesses, hence (Name) could face challenges in managing and developing others. 
As (Name) dislikes being the centre of attention and may be seen as uncertain, (Name) may find it uncomfortable managing and developing different groups of people as well as encouraging them to perform at their best. 
With a tendency to put more focus on getting the best outcome and to consider different factors, (Name) may get caught up with work details and miss out on opportunities to manage and develop people whilst keeping them accountable on their tasks.

competencies.name: Organizational Awareness

suggested_questions.name: Talk about an experience where you worked with individuals from other parts of the organisation who have different work practices and culture.
sub_questions: How did you familiarise yourself with the different work practises and culture?
What did you do to ensure alignment amidst the differences.
How did the co-working turn out at the end?

suggested_questions.name: Share a time when you were required to navigate work politics to achieve a particular objective.
sub_questions: How did you manage the work politics?
What challenges did you encounter and how did you resolve it?
What were your learnings from the experience?

positive_indicators: Highly attuned to the people, structure, and cultural context of the organisation.
Accurately anticipates the effect of decisions and actions on other parts of the organisation.
Highly skilled in navigating the influence dynamics of the organisation to establish alliances and achieve objectives.
negative_indicators: Has little interest or awareness of the people, structure, and cultural context of the organisation.
May operate within a silo and does not consider the effect of decisions and actions on other parts of the organisation.
Is unaware of the key decision makers or how to use these to achieve objectives.
competencies.score_description:
Though (Name) may overlook the long-term aspects and effect of decisions and actions on other parts of the organisation, (Name) tends to be aware of key factors in the people, structure and cultural context of the organisation.
(Name) generally has some interest in understanding the people and cultural context of the organisation, their behaviour and motivations as well as the organisational politics, but could pay more attention on the effect of decisions and actions on the people parts of the organisation while navigating the influence dynamics of the organisation.
(Name) is likely to understand the people, structure and cultural context of the organisation, regularly engaging with the people at work, however (Name) may face some difficulties navigating the influence dynamics within unfamiliar environments in the organisation.
(Name) has a likelihood of understanding the people, structure and cultural context of the organisation from a big picture viewpoint, but (Name) tends to focus more on implementation of decisions/actions into practice.

competencies.name: Innovation

suggested_questions.name: Share a situation where you challenged a traditional process or methodology?
sub_questions: How did you create and manage the new approach?
Which challenges did you face and how did you address them?

suggested_questions.name: Share a time where you suggested a new idea to your team/department.
sub_questions: How did you develop this idea? What were the driving factors behind the idea?
How did you convince relevant parties to accept and action on your idea?
Did you leverage on any sources to have your idea implemented?

positive_indicators: Consistently finds ways to innovate and improve on existing processes.
Excels in thinking out of the box and generating many ideas.
Role models communicating and enabling others to visualise new ideas and possibilities.
negative_indicators: Prefers to use tried and tested methods.
Lacks comfort with thinking out of the box and generating new ideas.
Is unable to communicate new ideas and possibilities.
competencies.score_description: (Name) is appreciative of new and novel ideas and solutions, helping others to visualise their new ideas, however, (Name) is more inclined to rely on the ideas of others, building upon them rather than generating own original ideas.\n(Name) is generally open to new and novel ideas/solutions or processes, however (Name) may still prefer the value of existing well-proven solutions, as (Name) may not prefer change for its own sake.\n(Name) tends to be able to attune to conceptual and abstract ideas and solutions, though (Name) is more inclined to focus on the implementation into practice, hence may only help others visualise ideas and possibilities that are tangible.

competencies.name: Effective Communication

suggested_questions.name: Describe a situation where you had to explain something complex to a colleague or a client.
sub_questions: How did you communicate the information?
How was the information received by the collegue/client?
What could you have done better to communicate more effectively?

suggested_questions.name: Share an experience where you faced a miscommunication/communication breakdown during a project
sub_questions: What was the cause of the miscommunocation?
What measures did you take to prevent it from happening again?

positive_indicators: Employs a variety of techniques/tailors the right style of communication to ensure audience understand the information clearly
Listens attentively when others speak to grasp message, and clarifies by asking probing questions
Speaks with confidence and conviction
Uses proper verbal and non verbal cues (facial expressions, eye contact, hand gestures etc) when listening and speaking
negative_indicators: Finds difficulty to communicate information clearly and with impact
Does not demonstrate empathy for target audience
Come across as inconsiderate or inattentive to others viewpoints
Lacks appropriate use of verbal/non verbal cues (facial expressions, eye contact, hand gestures etc)
competencies.score_description:
(Name) is likely able to communicate clear messages while influencing others with some confidence and impact when necessary, but may not do so proactively.
Fairly mindful of people's reaction and motives, (Name) is likely able to communicate messages convincingly, adapting them to the target audience, however could be more attentive as (Name) may at times overlook some opinions of others.
(Name) generally tends to be able to make sense of various topics and opinions of people, simplifying them into a comprehensive manner to communicate clear and concise messages.
When in familiar environments (Name) tends to be at ease putting forth clear and concise messages with confidence and impact, however (Name) may be more self-controlled when presenting messages in unfamiliar environments.
(Name) sees open communication as important factor but may not necessary believe that people always have to be adequately informed about all matters, hence (Name) may usually communicate clearly and concisely but may hold back information from certain people.

description.low: Accepts that pieces of information are restricted to certain people; takes rumours into account
description.high: Considers transparency and open communication crucial; always wants to be honest and overt

description.high: Is ambitious and actively looks for new challenges; wants to get ahead and succeed
description.competency_description: sets self-demanding targets; enjoys difficult challenges; wants to get ahead and succeed

description.high: Grasps complex issues quickly, evaluates facts and figures precisely and decides rationally
description.competency_description: quickly grasps complex issues and problems; identifies the core of a problem; evaluates information thoroughly

description.low: Is more effective in working alone; often misses to include and inform others actively
description.high: Is team-oriented and supportive; enjoys working with others and does that well
description.competency_description: is team-oriented and considerate; enjoys working with others; is supportive and pleasant to be with

description.low: Takes little interests in others’ motives; acts without considering their likely reactions
description.high: Observes and analyses others’ reactions; wants to understand their motives and behaviour
description.competency_description: is interested in others' behavior; observes and analyses others' motives and reactions

description.low: Prefers to work with concrete tasks; does not think of abstract strategies as helpful
description.high: Sees the links between issues; likes to work with abstract concepts; enjoys intellectual challenges
description.competency_description: enjoys working with concepts, models and strategies; likes intellectual challenges

description.low: Focuses strongly on short-term urgencies; seldom thinks about wider effects of actions
description.high: Takes a long-term comprehensive perspective; thinks far ahead and acts with foresight
description.competency_description: takes a broad perspective; considers the wider consequences of plans and activities

description.low: Feels more at ease without thorough plans; can appear to be unstructured or chaotic at times
description.high: Is systematic and well-organised; plans well ahead and defines clear priorities
description.competency_description: is systematic and well organized; defines clear priorities; plans well ahead and with realistic time-scales

description.low: Dislikes being overloaded; worries about setbacks; tends to become nervous under pressure
description.high: Works with a lot of drive and energy; remains focused and optimistic under pressure
description.competency_description: shows drive and determination; takes an energetic approach to work; remains focused and in control under pressure

description.low: Is down-to-earth and feels less creative; tends to stick with well tried and tested ideas
description.high: Develops many original ideas and innovative solutions; likes to be creative
description.competency_description: can think out of the box; develops imaginative and original ideas and solutions

description.low: Prefers well-proven methods and routine; meets change and innovation with reservations
description.high: Enjoys change and novelty; supports new ideas; questions traditional approaches
description.competency_description: supports new ideas; enjoys change and novelty; continually looks for ways to improve things

description.low: Provides others with the facts and figures, and then lets them decide for themselves
description.high: Enjoys selling and negotiating; knows how to persuade and win others for ideas
description.competency_description: enjoys selling and negotiating; finds it easy to persuade others; influences others and wins their support

description.low: Is rather stiff and insecure in unknown situations; feels more comfortable in familiar settings
description.high: Comes across as confident and self-assured; feels at ease during formal events
description.competency_description: comes across as confident and self-assured; feels at ease during presentations and formal events

description.low: Uncomfortable standing alone; adapts to majority votes; is cautious about airing strong opinions
description.high: Acts on own initiative, follows own direction; expresses own views freely
description.competency_description: acts on own initiative; follows own direction; expresses own views and opinions freely

description.low: Prefers cooperation over competition; leaves the credit for common work to others
description.high: Wants to win and do better than others; is motivated by competition; likes to stress own successes
description.competency_description: likes to compete against others; is determined to win; enjoys talking about own achievements

description.low: Looks for the best solution and wants to eliminate risks; could finish tasks more efficiently
description.high: Is target-oriented and pragmatic in approach; solves problems quickly and effectively
description.competency_description: is pragmatic and target-oriented in approach; focuses on reaching results; solves problems quickly and effectively

description.low: Leaves it to others to take charge and is reluctant to lead a group of people
description.high: Likes to manage and lead others; keeps a team focused on its objectives efficiently
description.competency_description: likes to be in charge; leads and directs others; keeps a team focused on objectives

description.low: Is quiet and reserved and likes to keep a distance; needs some time to make new contacts
description.high: Is talkative and sociable; entertains others and fosters a lot of contacts
description.competency_description: is talkative, lively and sociable; enjoys being in groups; entertains others and has a wide network of contacts

consistency_score.name: Consistency Score
consistency_score.description: A reliable consistency score (4-9) indicates a consistent, reliable answering pattern. A low consistency score could indicate that the candidate has not attempted the behavioural assessment seriously. When scores are low (1-3) or on an extreme high (10) it is advised to be more mindful of the scores. A consistency score of 10 indicates that the candidate had attempted to give answers that they felt the hiring manager would like to see.
